n2star  aThere are many stories featuring the villainous hero Reynard the Fox in many languages told over many centuries, goingback as far as the early 12th century. All these stories are comic and much of the humour depends on parody and satire resulting in mockery, sometimes the subversion of certain kinds of serious literature, of political and religious institutions and practices, of scholarly argument and moralizing, and of popular beliefs and customs. The contributors to this volume, all of them experts in one or more of the Reynard stories and their backgrounds, focus on the transformation of these tales through various media and to what extent they reflect differences in the cultural, class, and generational background of their tellers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aArt, MedievalzEngland. 0aFoxes in art. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBlock, Elaine C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaele, Rik van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDufournet, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoossens, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMann, Jill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPastré, Jean-Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchouwink, Wilfried, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStephenson, Roger H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSubrenat, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSuomela-Härmä, Elina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVarty, Kenneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVarty, Kenneth, eeditor.4edt4ht